  "extendedContent": [
    {
      "title": "Origins & Birth",
      "content": "Zeus, in Greek mythology, is the son of Cronus and Rhea, Titans who ruled the cosmos. Cronus, fearing a prophecy that one of his children would overthrow him, swallowed each of them at birth. Rhea, distraught, hid Zeus from Cronus by giving him a stone wrapped in swaddling clothes to swallow instead. She secretly delivered Zeus in a cave on Mount Ida in Crete. There, he was raised by the nymph Amalthea and protected by the Curetes, who clashed their spears and shields to mask the baby's cries. Once Zeus reached adulthood, he confronted Cronus and forced him to disgorge his siblings: Hades, Poseidon, Hestia, Demeter, and Hera. This event marked the beginning of the great war between the Olympian gods and the Titans, known as the Titanomachy, which would ultimately establish Zeus as the supreme ruler of the cosmos."
    },
    {
      "title": "Major Myths & Stories",
      "content": "Zeus is central to numerous Greek myths. The Titanomachy, a decade-long war, saw Zeus and his siblings overthrow the Titans with the help of the Cyclopes, who forged Zeus's thunderbolts. Another prominent myth is Zeus's defeat of the monster Typhon, a fearsome creature sent by Gaia to challenge the Olympian order. Zeus is also known for his numerous affairs with both goddesses and mortal women, resulting in the births of many heroes and demigods, including Heracles, Perseus, and Helen of Troy. These affairs often led to conflicts with his wife, Hera, who was known for her jealousy and vengeful actions against Zeus's lovers and their offspring. Zeus's reign was marked by both his power and his complex relationships, shaping the landscape of Greek mythology."
    },
    {
      "title": "Worship & Cult",
      "content": "The worship of Zeus was widespread throughout the ancient Greek world. Temples and altars dedicated to him were erected in prominent locations, such as Olympia, where the Olympic Games were held in his honor. Sacrifices of animals, particularly bulls, were common offerings, as were libations of wine and honey. Zeus was invoked in oaths and treaties, and his name was considered sacred. Different aspects of Zeus were worshipped under various epithets, reflecting his diverse roles and attributes. For example, Zeus Horkios was the protector of oaths, while Zeus Xenios was the protector of guests and travelers. Festivals, such as the Diasia in Athens, were celebrated to honor Zeus and seek his favor. His cult played a central role in the religious and social life of ancient Greece."
    },
    {
      "title": "Legacy & Influence",
      "content": "Zeus's influence extends far beyond ancient Greece. As the king of the gods, he represents power, authority, and justice. His stories and attributes have been adapted and reinterpreted in countless works of art, literature, and popular culture. From Renaissance paintings to modern films, Zeus remains a recognizable and compelling figure. His name and symbols are often used to evoke a sense of grandeur and divine power. The Roman equivalent of Zeus, Jupiter, also shares a similar legacy, further solidifying the god's enduring impact on Western culture. The study of Zeus and his mythology provides valuable insights into the beliefs, values, and worldview of the ancient Greeks, and his influence continues to resonate in contemporary society."
    }
  ],
